{"cursor":"7465","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nAn 'exon' is any nucleotide sequence encoded by a gene that remains present\nwithin the final mature RNA product of that gene after introns have been removed\nby RNA splicing. The term exon refers to both the DNA sequence within a gene and\nto the corresponding sequence in RNA transcripts. In RNA splicing, introns are\nremoved and exons are covalently joined to one another as part of generating the\nmature messenger RNA or noncoding RNA product of a gene.\n","linknr":288,"url":"Exon","recorded":1362374189,"links":40,"instances":["genetics","genetics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["DNA","Spliceosome","RNA splicing"],"headings":["History","Experimental approaches that utilize exons","See also","References","General references","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Gene_structure.svg/480px-Gene_structure.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["transcription","genetics"],["enhancer","genetics"]],"members":["transcription","enhancer"],"related":["Gene","Introns","RNA_splicing","Messenger_RNA","Noncoding_RNA","Biochemistry","Walter_Gilbert","Cistron","RRNA","TRNA","Genes","Open_reading_frame","Protein","Pre-mRNA","Amino_acids","Intron","Messenger_RNA","Five_prime_untranslated_region","Three_prime_untranslated_region","Transcription_(genetics)","Alternative_splicing","Non-coding_RNA","Intron","Polycistronic","Exon_trapping","Gene_trapping","Molecular_biology","RNA_splicing","Insertional_DNA","Reporter_gene","Enhancer_(genetics)","Morpholino","Developmental_biology","Eukaryotic_gene_example","Exon_shuffling","Interrupted_gene","Intron","MRNA","Untranslated_regi